[1] EEE, equine - Florida
Date: 12 Sep 2012
Source: Tallahasee.com [edited]
http://www.tallahassee.com/article/20120912/TLHLOCAL/120912016/Leon-County-horses-test-positive-mosquito-borne-illness-?&nclick_check=1


Leon County horses test positive for mosquito-borne illness
-----------------------------------------------------------
So far, 2 horses within one mile of each other in the Fort Braden area near Highway 20 have tested positive for Eastern equine encephalitis virus (EEE), reports the Florida Department of Health (DOH).

EEE is a mosquito-borne illness that is nearly always fatal to horses contracting it. Another horse in the Woodville area tested positive for the disease yesterday [11 Sep 2012].

These cases, combined with the 1st human case of West Nile virus in Gadsden County, reported yesterday, and Leon County's 1st human case, reported in late August, have the DOH on high alert for mosquito-borne diseases. The DOH recommends all precautions against possible infections, including regular standing water drainage, covering skin with clothes or repellent, covering windows and doors to keep mosquitoes out, and protecting pets from mosquito bites.

State officials will continue to conduct statewide surveillance for mosquito-borne illnesses, including West Nile virus infections, Eastern equine encephalitis, St. Louis encephalitis, malaria and dengue.

[Byline: Jordan Culver]

